cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.HC, cs.MM 

The paper deals with analyzing behavior in crowded public places using computer vision techniques, which suggests that it could belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also proposes a clustering-based algorithm and two methods for motion novelty inference, which involve machine learning techniques, indicating that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the intentionality and goal-oriented planning of human motion, which suggests that it could belong to the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its algorithms on a video, indicating that it could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
